        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "MQTT is completely decoupled from the bundle format. Here's how the two paths work:\n\n**MQTT ingress** (receiving from MQTT broker): The `MqttBridge` subscriber receives raw `WirePayload` bytes from MQTT topics, decodes them into `OuterEnvelope`, and calls `store.enqueue()` directly. It never touches the HTTP submit endpoint or the bundle format.\n\n**MQTT egress** (publishing to MQTT broker): When the node receives a message via HTTP submit, `MqttBridge::publish` takes a decoded `OuterEnvelope`, encodes it as raw `WirePayload` bytes, and publishes to MQTT topic `{prefix}/messages/{hex_routing_key}`. No bundle wrapping.\n\n**MQTT client transport** (`MqttTarget::submit_message`): Encodes as raw `WirePayload` bytes and publishes to MQTT topics at QoS1. No bundle format, no HTTP.\n\nSo MQTT uses its own topic-based multiplexing — each message goes to its own topic by routing key. There's no concept of \"batching\" because MQTT's pub/sub model naturally handles individual messages. The bundle format is HTTP-specific — it exists because HTTP has per-request overhead (connection, headers, TLS handshake) that batching amortizes. MQTT doesn't have that problem.\n\nNo gap here. MQTT and bundles are orthogonal by design.",
