detect at runtime whether the terminal supports true-color, 256-color, or basic 8-color; detect italic/bold support.\n- Applicable? Mildly useful. Currently `reme` hardcodes `Color::DarkGray`, `Color::Cyan`, etc. which degrade gracefully on terminals that downgrade colors, but it does not gracefully adapt its style choices. If reme ever adds richer styling or a theme system, `termprofile` would be useful to gate true-color palettes. Not urgent, but low-risk to add.\n\n**`tui-input`**\n- Use case: headless (stateless) text input line editing, separate from rendering.\n- Applicable? **Partially superseded.** `reme` already uses `tui-textarea` (0.7) which handles all text input (the `TextArea<'a>` fields in `AddContactPopup` and `AddUpstreamPopup`). `tui-input` is a lighter alternative for single-line inputs, but the migration cost from `tui-textarea` with no functional gain makes this a lateral move. Keep `tui-textarea`.\n\n**`tui-pantry`**\n- Use case: component dev tool / storybook for isolated widget rendering.\n- Applicable? Yes, as a `[dev-dependencies]` only tool for TUI development ergonomics. It would help visually test individual popups without running the full app stack. Low security impact since it's dev-only. Worth considering once the widget count grows — not urgent at current scale.\n\n**`tui-syntax-highlight`**\n- Use case: syntax-highlighted code block rendering using tree-sitter.\n- Applicable? No. `reme` is a messaging client, not a code viewer. Messages are plaintext. Unless you plan to render inline code snippets with highlighting (a feature that does not exist), irrelevant. Tree-sitter is also a non-trivial dependency footprint.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Library | Adopt? | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| `ratatui-macros` | **Yes** | Eliminates `chunks[N]` index errors; first-party crate; direct hit on `ui.rs` layout boilerplate |\n| `terminput` | **No** | Adds abstraction with zero benefit; conflicts with tui-textarea crossterm types |\n| `tui-pantry` | **Maybe** (dev-dep) | Useful as widget isolation harness when popup count grows |\n| `termprofile` | **Maybe** | Only if a theme/color-capability adaptation system is planned |\n| `color-to-tui` | **No** (yet) | Only needed when config-driven theming is added |\n| `tui-input` | **No** | tui-textarea already covers all input use cases |\n| `ratatui-interact` | **No** | Focus model is already clean; mouse is out of scope |\n| `tui-syntax-highlight` | **No** | No code display use case |\n| `ansi-to-tui` | **No** | No ANSI input pipeline |\n| `coolor` | **No** | No color math |\n| `tachyonfx` | **No** | Inappropriate for a secure messaging client |\n| `ratatui-garnish` | **No** | Popup composition does not justify the framework overhead |\n\nThe only actionable recommendation is `ratatui-macros`. It is officially maintained by the ratatui team (lives in the ratatui-org GitHub org), has essentially no supply-chain surface area, and directly addresses the most real correctness risk in the current UI code: numeric chunk indexing.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>42130</total_tokens><tool_uses>12</tool_uses><duration_ms>86397</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/cde6fd4c-88a8-464b-941a-e71717209706/tasks/a9600e5b3a2740e02.output",
