ge identity.\n\n3. **Per-chunk integrity verification:** The three-layer integrity chain (chunk hash -> transfer hash -> VSF hash) is overkill for reme's HTTP-based transport (TLS provides integrity), but would be relevant if reme adds UDP or BLE transports where corruption is possible.\n\n**What NOT to adopt:** The Blast-256 congestion control is inappropriate for reme. It is designed for dedicated peer-to-peer links and would be hostile on shared internet paths. If reme ever adds UDP transport, standard CUBIC or BBR congestion control would be more appropriate.\n\n### 4. LAN Discovery Approach\n\n**Photon** (`NETWORK.md` lines 64-96, `status.rs` line 142-148):\n- Raw UDP broadcast to `255.255.255.255:4383` with a VSF packet containing `handle_proof` and `port`.\n- Very simple: broadcast IP, parse responses, match by handle_proof.\n- No service type abstraction, no DNS-SD, no multicast.\n- NAT hairpinning: FGTW bootstrap includes `local_ip` field so peers behind the same public IP can use LAN addresses instead.\n- LAN discovery is a single request type (`pt_disc`) discriminated at the packet level.\n\n**reme** (`crates/reme-discovery/`):\n- Proper mDNS-SD using the `mdns_sd` crate, browsing `_reme._tcp.local.`.\n- `DiscoveryBackend` trait (in `backend.rs`) abstracts over discovery mechanisms (mDNS, future BLE).\n- `AdvertisementSpec` includes routing key, port, TXT records, and service type.\n- Privacy-preserving instance names derived from routing key (noted in `types.rs` line 48-49).\n- Structured event system: `PeerDiscovered`, `PeerUpdated`, `PeerLost` events via broadcast channels.\n- Full verification flow: discovered peers are verified via HTTP challenge-response before being registered as ephemeral targets.\n\n**Assessment:** reme's approach is strictly superior:\n- mDNS multicast is more reliable than raw broadcast (works across VLANs with mDNS relay, respects network topology).\n- DNS-SD provides structured metadata via TXT records.\n- Privacy-preserving instance names avoid leaking machine hostnames (Photon broadcasts `handle_proof` in the clear).\n- The `DiscoveryBackend` trait enables future backends (BLE, etc.) without changing the discovery controller.\n- The verification step (HTTP challenge-response) prevents impersonation attacks that Photon's broadcast-and-trust model is vulnerable to.\n\n**One thing to adopt from Photon:** The `local_ip` field in FGTW's bootstrap response (line 566-584 in `bootstrap.rs`). When reme eventually has WAN relay nodes, those nodes could include the sender's local IP in the peer record. This helps with NAT hairpinning when two peers are behind the same NAT but discover each other through a remote relay.\n\n### 5. Bootstrap/Peer Store Patterns\n\n**Photon's PeerStore** (`src/network/fgtw/peer_store.rs`):\n- Sorted `Vec<PeerRecord>` with binary search by `handle_proof` (line 20-24).\n- Multiple devices per handle (consecutive entries with same handle_proof).\n- Time-based expiry using `PEER_EXPIRY_OSC` (7 days, line 64).\n- `cleanup_stale()` for periodic garbage collection (line 122-128).\n\n**Photon's bootstrap** (`src/network/fgtw/bootstrap.rs`):\n- Central server (FGTW at `https://fgtw.org`) with challenge-response authentication.\n- Challenge: fetch signed nonce from FGTW, verify FGTW's Ed25519 signature (hardcoded pubkey, lines 17-26).\n- Announce: encrypt (ephemeral X25519 + AES-256-GCM) the handle_proof, port, and local_ip to FGTW's public key. FGTW responds with encrypted peer list.\n- The encrypted announce/response is a reasonable pattern: it prevents passive observers from learning peer associations.\n\n**What's reusable for reme:**\n\n1. **Multi-device peer records:** Photon's PeerStore supports multiple devices per user identity. reme currently does not have multi-device support, but when it does, a similar sorted-vec-with-binary-search pattern is efficient and simple.\n\n2. **Encrypted bootstrap exchange:** If reme ever introduces decentralized relay discovery, the pattern of encrypting the announce payload to the bootstrap server's public key (preventing passive enumeration of users) is worth adopting.\n\n3. **Time-based peer expiry with configurable TTL:** reme's `refresh_interval_secs` (default 300) for peer re-verification is more aggressive than Photon's 7-day expiry. Both are valid for their contexts (reme's ephemeral LAN peers vs Photon's WAN peer directory).\n\n### 6. Status/Ping-Pong Protocol\n\n**Photon** (`src/network/fgtw/protocol.rs` lines 37-76, `src/network/status.rs`):\n- `StatusPing`: Contains Eagle Time timestamp, sender pubkey, BLAKE3 provenance hash (`BLAKE3(sender_pubkey || timestamp_nanos)`), and Ed25519 signature over the provenance hash.\n- `StatusPong`: Echoes the same provenance hash (proves it was received), plus per-conversation `SyncRecord` entries with `last_received_osc` for efficient resync.\n- The sync records in pong are notable: they tell the peer \"for conversation X, the last message I received was at time Y\", enabling the peer to retransmit only what was missed.\n- Replay protection via provenance hash (timestamp + pubkey).\n- Hysteresis for offline detection: `failed_pings` counter (line 649 in `status.rs`) prevents flapping on single lost packets.\n\n**reme's peer verification** (from `CLAUDE.md` architecture description):\n- HTTP challenge-response: discovered mDNS peers are verified by sending a challenge to their embedded HTTP server.\n- Two consecutive verification failures trigger removal (ephemeral circuit breaker).\n- No sync record exchange -- message synchronization happens through DAG heads and tombstones.\n\n**Assessment and recommendations:**\n\n1. **Sync records in pong:** This is a genuinely useful pattern. Photon's pong includes \"here's where I am in each conversation\" which enables efficient retransmission. reme achieves similar functionality through DAG `observed_heads`, but those are per-message overhead. A lightweight sync exchange during peer verification could reduce unnecessary retransmission, especially after reconnection. Worth considering for reme's Phase 2 maintenance refresh.\n\n2. **Provenance hash replay protection:** reme's HTTP challenge-response achieves the same goal but with an extra round trip. For a future UDP-based ping, Photon's approach (timestamp + pubkey hash) is more efficient.\n\n3. **Hysteresis:** reme's \"two consecutive failures\" circuit breaker is simpler and adequate. Photon's counter-based approach would be useful if reme adds more aggressive peer liveness checking.\n\n### Summary of Actionable Takeaways\n\n| Finding | Priority | Action |\n|---------|----------|--------|\n| Sync records in pong | Medium | Consider adding DAG-head exchange to peer verification refresh |\n| Fallback cascade in `tick()` | Low | Design pattern reference for outbox improvements |\n| Local IP in relay peer records | Low | Useful when adding WAN relay discovery for NAT hairpinning |\n| Multi-device peer records | Low | Reference for future multi-device support |\n| Direct UDP transport | Not recommended | Embedded HTTP covers LAN; WebRTC better for WAN |\n| Blast-256 congestion control | Not recommended | Too aggressive for shared internet paths |\n| Raw broadcast for LAN discovery | Not recommended | reme's mDNS-SD is strictly better |</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>82946</total_tokens><tool_uses>31</tool_uses><duration_ms>158399</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/4ca7ec16-3e71-496c-91e6-56c7de96f6b4/tasks/a7bceaf3d5893738e.output",
