            "command": "gh issue edit 180 --body \"$(cat <<'GHEOF'\n## Problem\n\nThe `/api/v1/identity` endpoint is an identity oracle. It signs any challenge from any requester without authentication. An attacker on the LAN can:\n\n1. Enumerate all IPs on the subnet (trivial)\n2. Send a challenge to each IP's identity endpoint\n3. Try verifying the returned signature against a set of known/guessed PublicIDs\n4. Build a complete `IP → PublicID` map\n\nThe response intentionally omits the public key, but brute-forcing against a small candidate set (contacts list, scraped keys, etc.) is trivial — one XEdDSA verify per candidate per IP.\n\nThis is exploitable **regardless of mDNS configuration**. Even with routing key broadcast disabled and future privacy-preserving mDNS improvements, the identity endpoint remains an unconditional oracle.\n\n### Current flow\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant C as Challenger\n    participant R as Responder\n\n    C->>R: GET /identity?challenge=<rand>\n    Note right of R: sign(challenge || own_pubkey)\n    R-->>C: { signature }\n    Note left of C: try verify(sig, candidate_keys)\n```\n\nThe responder signs for anyone. The challenger can be a stranger, a bot, a surveillance device.\n\n### Related issues\n\n- #116 — channel binding (SEC-3): responder IP:port not in signed data (MITM relay attack)\n- #104 — rate-limit identity endpoint (hardening, doesn't solve the oracle)\n- #146 — mDNS instance name privacy (complementary but orthogonal)\n\n## Proposed options\n\n### Option A: Challenger commits to target routing key\n\nThe challenger proves they already know who they're looking for by including a commitment in the request. The responder only signs if the commitment matches.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant C as Challenger\n    participant R as Responder\n\n    C->>R: challenge + BLAKE3(nonce || target_rk)\n    Note right of R: commitment matches<br/>own routing_key?\n    alt match\n        R-->>C: { signature }\n    else no match\n        R-->>C: 404\n    end\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Single round trip (same as today)\n- Prevents blind enumeration — attacker must already know the target's routing key\n- Simple to implement\n- Backward-compatible if commitment is optional during migration\n\n**Cons:**\n- One-directional: responder still doesn't know who's asking\n- Attacker with a routing key list can still probe (but must be targeted, not blind)\n- Routing key is 16 bytes (truncated BLAKE3 of PublicID) — smaller search space than PublicID\n\n### Option B: Mutual challenge-response (two rounds)\n\nBoth parties authenticate. The challenger proves their own identity too.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant C as Challenger\n    participant R as Responder\n\n    C->>R: challenger_pubkey + challenge_a<br/>+ commitment(target_rk)\n    Note right of R: verify commitment<br/>check challenger<br/>is known contact\n\n    R-->>C: signature_b(challenge_a)<br/>+ challenge_b\n\n    C->>R: signature_a(challenge_b)\n    Note over C,R: Both verified\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Both parties authenticated — responder knows who asked\n- Responder can enforce policy (only respond to known contacts)\n- Foundation for trust level upgrades (#179) — mutual verification could auto-promote to `Verified`\n- Strongest defense against enumeration\n\n**Cons:**\n- Two extra round trips (3 total) — higher latency for discovery\n- More complex protocol and state management\n- Responder must hold challenger state between rounds (stateful endpoint)\n\n### Option C: ECDH-gated response (one round, encrypted)\n\nChallenger sends an ephemeral X25519 pubkey + the target routing key encrypted to the responder. The responder decrypts, checks if it matches, and only then signs — encrypted response back.\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant C as Challenger\n    participant R as Responder\n\n    C->>R: ephemeral_pubkey +<br/>Enc(target_rk, ECDH(eph, responder))\n    Note right of R: ECDH(own_mik, eph)<br/>decrypt target_rk<br/>matches? → sign\n    alt match\n        R-->>C: Enc(signature, shared_secret)\n    else no match\n        R-->>C: 404 (silent reject)\n    end\n```\n\n**Pros:**\n- Single round trip\n- Prevents enumeration (responder rejects non-matching requests silently)\n- Encrypted query — eavesdropper can't see which routing key is being queried\n- Encrypted response — eavesdropper can't see the signature\n- Reuses reme's existing X25519 + ChaCha20Poly1305 primitives\n- Conceptually aligned with reme's stateless encryption model\n\n**Cons:**\n- Requires the challenger to know the responder's PublicID (not just routing key) for ECDH — but the challenger already has this from the contacts list\n- Still one-directional (responder doesn't learn challenger's persistent identity)\n- More complex than Option A\n- The responder's MIK is used for ECDH here, which is fine (already used for message decryption) but widens the MIK usage surface\n\n### Option D: Hybrid — Option A now, Option B or C later\n\nShip the commitment check (Option A) as an immediate hardening step, then layer on mutual auth or ECDH-gating in a future version.\n\n**Pros:**\n- Fast to ship, breaks the oracle immediately\n- Migration path via protocol versioning (`reme-identity-v2:` prefix)\n- Doesn't block on designing the full mutual auth protocol\n\n**Cons:**\n- Two protocol changes instead of one\n- Option A might calcify if \"good enough\" prevents follow-through\n\n## Recommendation\n\n**Option D** (A now, C later) balances immediacy with ambition. The commitment check is a one-session fix that closes the blind enumeration attack. ECDH-gating is the ideal end state but needs more design work (especially around the \"challenger must know responder's PublicID\" requirement and how that interacts with stranger discovery).\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Identity endpoint rejects requests without valid commitment\n- [ ] Commitment uses `BLAKE3(\"reme-identity-commitment-v1:\" || challenger_nonce || target_routing_key)`\n- [ ] Responder returns 404 (not 403) on mismatch to avoid leaking \"this is a reme node\"\n- [ ] Existing tests updated\n- [ ] Protocol version bumped in signed data prefix\n- [ ] Migration period: accept both committed and uncommitted requests behind a config flag, default to committed-only\n\n## References\n\n- #116 — channel binding (complementary, can be addressed in same protocol bump)\n- #104 — rate limiting (still useful as defense-in-depth alongside this)\n- #146 — mDNS privacy (orthogonal but thematically related)\n- #179 — TrustLevel for contacts (mutual auth feeds into trust promotion)\n- Photon uses `handle_proof` in broadcast (weaker — broadcasts identity in the clear)\nGHEOF\n)\"",
