          "text": "\n\nNot a real concern. They operate at different layers and serve different purposes:\n\n**Tor encrypts the transport** — it wraps TCP packets in 3 layers of circuit encryption so relay nodes can't read the content or correlate sender/receiver. This is hop-by-hop, stripped at each relay. It protects *routing metadata*.\n\n**reme encrypts the message** — ephemeral X25519 ECDH + ChaCha20Poly1305 protects the *payload*. Only the recipient with the right MIK can decrypt. This is end-to-end, independent of transport.\n\nRemoving either one would be a security regression:\n- Without Tor encryption: relay nodes read your traffic (defeats the point of Tor)\n- Without reme encryption: the exit/rendezvous point reads your messages (defeats E2E)\n\n**Performance impact is negligible.** ChaCha20Poly1305 runs at ~1GB/s on modern CPUs. reme messages are typically <2KB. The double encryption adds microseconds. Tor's latency (300-800ms) comes from 6 network hops across the globe, not from crypto overhead.\n\nThis is the same layering every messenger uses over TLS — Signal's Double Ratchet runs inside TLS, WhatsApp's E2E runs inside TLS. Nobody strips the inner encryption because TLS \"already encrypts.\" They protect against different threats.",
