 373). This creates a SOCKS connection through the local Tor daemon. Incoming connections arrive on the local ServerSocket.\n\n**Reliability concerns:**\n- Hidden service publication can fail silently (line 252, just logs the exception).\n- Connection timeouts are generous: `EXTRA_CONNECT_TIMEOUT = 120s`, `EXTRA_SOCKET_TIMEOUT = 30s` (TorConstants lines 15-16).\n- The plugin has sophisticated network-awareness: it disables Tor when on mobile data (configurable), when not charging (configurable), and auto-configures bridges (Meek, Snowflake) based on country code via `CircumventionProvider` (lines 536-549).\n- Backoff with exponential retry is used for polling intervals.\n\n**Rendezvous onion derivation** (`createRendezvousEndpoint`, line 410): For adding new contacts, Briar derives deterministic Ed25519 key pairs from shared key material. Both peers independently compute each other's ephemeral onion addresses and connect. This is used for the \"pending contact\" flow -- both sides publish a temporary hidden service derived from the link code, enabling contact exchange without any other channel.\n\n**Implications for reme:** If reme adds Tor hidden service support, the key lessons are:\n- Startup time is the main UX problem. Tor bootstrap can take 10-30 seconds on mobile, longer with bridges. Briar handles this with an `ENABLING` state and background startup.\n- Hidden service publication is asynchronous and can fail. You need to handle the case where the hidden service is not yet available.\n- Bridge support is essential for censorship resistance but adds complexity.\n- The rendezvous pattern (deterministic onion addresses from shared secrets) is elegant for contact exchange. reme's mDNS verification flow serves a similar purpose on LAN but Tor rendezvous works across the internet without a shared relay.\n- Briar does NOT use Tor for store-and-forward. Each connection is a live bidirectional stream. reme's mailbox-based architecture is fundamentally different -- reme could use Tor as a transport for reaching the mailbox HTTP server (similar to how Briar's mailbox does it), rather than for direct peer-to-peer connections.\n\n### 2. Bluetooth Transport\n\n**Key files:**\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-core/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/plugin/bluetooth/AbstractBluetoothPlugin.java`\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-android/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/plugin/bluetooth/AndroidBluetoothPlugin.java`\n\n**Architecture:** Briar uses **Classic Bluetooth RFCOMM**, not BLE mesh. The `AbstractBluetoothPlugin` (660 lines) is an abstract `DuplexPlugin` with platform-specific subclasses (Android, potentially others). There is no BLE implementation at all.\n\n**How it works:**\n- Each device generates a random UUID (line 261) stored as transport property `PROP_UUID`, and shares its Bluetooth MAC address (`PROP_ADDRESS`).\n- A server socket is opened on the UUID to accept incoming connections (line 215).\n- To connect to a contact, the plugin uses the contact's MAC address and UUID (line 399).\n- Discovery fallback: if the MAC address is unknown, `discoverAndConnect(uuid)` triggers Bluetooth device discovery (line 471).\n- `BluetoothConnectionLimiter` limits concurrent connections to avoid resource exhaustion.\n\n**Reflected address mechanism** (lines 282-296): Since Android 6+, apps cannot read the local Bluetooth MAC address. Briar works around this by having contacts report back the MAC address they see (\"reflected address\"). A voting mechanism -- if more than half of contacts agree on an address -- accepts it. This is clever but fragile.\n\n**Real-world limitations:**\n- Classic Bluetooth RFCOMM, not BLE. No mesh capability.\n- Requires devices to be in close physical proximity and paired/discoverable.\n- `supportsRendezvous()` returns `false` (line 524) -- Bluetooth cannot be used for contact exchange without physical proximity.\n- Connection limiter suggests real resource constraints in practice.\n- The reflected MAC address voting is a workaround for API restrictions, not a robust discovery mechanism.\n\n**Implications for reme:** Bluetooth is a close-range transport only. It maps to reme's future Tier 3 (BestEffort). If reme adds BLE, it should be understood as a last-resort, local-area fallback rather than a mesh network. Briar does not attempt mesh routing over Bluetooth -- each connection is point-to-point RFCOMM. For reme's DTN goals, LoRa/Meshtastic is a better fit for extended-range BestEffort delivery.\n\n### 3. LAN Transport\n\n**Key files:**\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-core/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/plugin/tcp/LanTcpPlugin.java`\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-core/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/plugin/tcp/TcpPlugin.java`\n\n**How Briar does LAN discovery:** Briar does NOT use mDNS. Instead, it relies on Transport Properties shared via BSP (the sync protocol). Each device:\n1. Enumerates local network interfaces for link-local and site-local IPv4 addresses, plus link-local IPv6 addresses (line 176-188).\n2. Binds a TCP `ServerSocket` on a preferred port (persisted, or random from 32768-65535).\n3. Publishes its IP:port list as transport property `PROP_IP_PORTS` (shared with contacts).\n4. When polling, tries to connect to each contact's known IP:port addresses.\n5. Also probes well-known Android hotspot addresses (192.168.43.1, 192.168.49.1) as fallbacks (lines 257-264).\n6. Connectivity check: verifies remote address is on the same subnet using prefix length comparison (`areAddressesInSameNetwork`, line 321).\n7. Maintains separate IPv4 and IPv6 server sockets with independent state.\n\n**Comparison with reme's mDNS approach:**\n\n| Aspect | Briar LAN TCP | reme mDNS |\n|--------|---------------|-----------|\n| Discovery | IP:port shared via encrypted contact sync | mDNS-SD `_reme._tcp.local.` broadcast |\n| Privacy | Addresses only visible to contacts | mDNS broadcasts visible to all LAN devices |\n| Identity verification | BTP transport-layer auth | HTTP challenge-response verification |\n| Unknown contacts | Cannot discover non-contacts | Can discover any mDNS peer, verification needed |\n| IP changes | Must re-sync properties | mDNS automatically updates |\n| Fallback | Probes known hotspot IPs | N/A |\n\n**Key insight:** Briar's approach is more privacy-preserving because address information flows through the existing encrypted sync channel. reme's mDNS broadcast reveals that a reme instance is running on the network to anyone who can see mDNS traffic. The `mdns-privacy-instance-name` spec in `docs/superpowers/specs/` suggests reme is already aware of this concern.\n\nHowever, reme's approach is more dynamic -- mDNS handles IP changes and new devices automatically, while Briar requires property re-sync. For reme's auto-direct-known-contacts flow, mDNS is the right choice since it needs to discover peers before it knows if they are contacts. The subsequent identity verification step compensates for the privacy trade-off.\n\n### 4. Mailbox Architecture\n\n**Key files:**\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-core/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/mailbox/MailboxApi.java`\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-api/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/api/mailbox/MailboxProperties.java`\n- `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar/bramble-core/src/main/java/org/briarproject/bramble/plugin/file/MailboxPlugin.java`\n\n**Briar's mailbox model:**\n\nBriar's mailbox is a fundamentally different design from reme's:\n\n1. **Per-user dedicated hardware**: A Briar mailbox is a personal device (e.g., Raspberry Pi) paired to a single owner. It is NOT a shared relay.\n2. **Tor hidden service**: The mailbox runs as a Tor hidden service (`MailboxProperties.onion`). All communication is over Tor.\n3. **Token-based auth**: Owner gets an `MailboxAuthToken` during QR-code pairing. The owner creates per-contact auth tokens with separate inbox/outbox folder IDs.\n4. **File-based API**: Messages are uploaded/downloaded as opaque files via REST endpoints (`addFile`, `getFiles`, `getFile`, `deleteFile`). The mailbox never sees plaintext -- it just stores encrypted blobs.\n5. **Simplex transport**: `MailboxPlugin` extends `FilePlugin` which implements `SimplexPlugin`. Upload and download are separate unidirectional operations. This is important: the mailbox plugin is a simplex transport with its own BTP key set, separate from the duplex Tor transport.\n6. **Folder structure**: Owner can add files to contacts' inboxes. Contacts can add files to their own outboxes. Owner polls `getFolders()` to list outboxes with pending files.\n\n**Comparison with reme's mailbox:**\n\n| Aspect | Briar Mailbox | reme Mailbox |\n|--------|---------------|--------------|\n| Deployment | Per-user dedicated device | Shared relay nodes |\n| Transport | Tor hidden service (HTTP over .onion) | Plain HTTP(S), MQTT |\n| Auth | Per-contact auth tokens | URL-embedded credentials or TLS certs |\n| Storage model | Opaque file blobs with folder IDs | OuterEnvelopes keyed by routing_key |\n| Addressing | Owner assigns inbox/outbox folders | RoutingKey (truncated blake3 of PublicID) |\n| Trust model | Only your mailbox, you control it | Trust the relay operator somewhat |\n| Cleanup | Client calls `deleteFile` | Tombstone V2 with ack_secret |\n| Multi-relay | No (one mailbox per user) | Yes (quorum across multiple relays) |\n\n**Key architectural difference:** Briar's mailbox is trust-minimized by being personally owned. It never learns who is communicating (folder IDs are random). reme's relay nodes are shared infrastructure that could be operated by anyone -- the routing_key design hides identity but the relay operator sees traffic patterns. reme compensates with quorum delivery across multiple relays.\n\nBriar's approach is philosophically purer but operationally harder (requires always-on hardware). reme's shared-relay approach is more practical for deployment but requires more trust assumptions.\n\n### 5. Transport Plugin Abstraction\n\n**Briar's plugin hierarchy:**\n\n```\nPlugin (base: start/stop/poll/state)\n├── DuplexPlugin (bidirectional streams: createConnection, keyAgreement, rendezvous)\n│   ├── TorPlugin\n│   ├── TcpPlugin → LanTcpPlugin, WanTcpPlugin\n│   └── AbstractBluetoothPlugin → AndroidBluetoothPlugin\n└── SimplexPlugin (unidirectional: createReader, createWriter, isLossyAndCheap)\n    ├── FilePlugin → MailboxPlugin, RemovableDrivePlugin\n    └── (future: LoRa?)\n```\n\nSupporting types:\n- `PluginFactory<P extends Plugin>`: Creates plugins, provides transport ID and max latency.\n- `PluginCallback`: Bi-directional interface between plugin and framework. Provides settings, local/remote transport properties, handles incoming connections.\n- `PluginManager`: Lifecycle management -- starts all plugins at startup, stops at shutdown. Queries for key-agreement and rendezvous plugins.\n- `TransportProperties`: Per-contact, per-transport key-value properties (like onion address, BT MAC, IP:port).\n- `Backoff`: Exponential backoff for polling.\n- `ConnectionHandler`: Callback for incoming connections.\n\n**reme's transport architecture:**\n\n```\nTransport (trait: submit_message, submit_ack_tombstone)\n├── HttpTransport (legacy, wraps a single URL)\n├── CompositeTransport (wraps multiple targets)\n└── (unused directly -- TransportTarget is the modern abstraction)\n\nTransportTarget (trait: submit_message, fetch_messages, submit_ack_tombstone)\n├── HttpTarget\n├── MqttTarget\n├── EmbeddedTarget\n└── (future targets)\n\nTransportCoordinator (orchestrates targets via TransportRegistry)\n├── TieredDelivery (Tier 1 Direct, Tier 2 Quorum, Tier 3 BestEffort)\n└── TransportRegistry (manages target lifecycle, health tracking)\n```\n\n**Comparison:**\n\n| Aspect | Briar Plugin | reme Transport |\n|--------|-------------|----------------|\n| Direction | Duplex vs Simplex distinction | All targets are conceptually simplex (submit/fetch) |\n| State machine | STARTING_STOPPING → DISABLED → ENABLING → ACTIVE → INACTIVE | Health-based (Healthy/Degraded/Unreachable) |\n| Discovery | Plugins handle own discovery + properties sync | Separate discovery layer (mDNS) |\n| Key agreement | Built into DuplexPlugin interface | Not part of transport trait |\n| Rendezvous | Built into DuplexPlugin interface | Not applicable (stateless encryption) |\n| Polling | Plugin implements shouldPoll/getPollingInterval | Coordinator handles fetch scheduling |\n| Multi-target | One plugin instance per transport type | Multiple targets per transport type (via Registry) |\n| Tiered delivery | Not applicable (all transports equal) | Explicit tier classification |\n\n**Is Briar's more extensible?** In some ways, yes. Briar's Duplex/Simplex split is genuinely useful -- it captures a real property of transport channels. A LoRa link that can only send is fundamentally different from a TCP connection. reme currently treats everything as a target that supports `submit_message()` and `fetch_messages()`, which works for HTTP and MQTT but may be awkward for truly unidirectional or stream-oriented transports.\n\nHowever, reme's `TransportTarget` + `TransportRegistry` + `TieredDelivery` composition is more sophisticated for the multi-relay case. Briar has exactly one connection per contact per transport; reme can have N targets per transport type with independent health and quorum requirements.\n\n**Recommendation:** reme should NOT adopt Briar's plugin model wholesale. However, it would benefit from:\n1. Adding a `TransportCapability` enum (or similar) to express whether a target is send-only, fetch-only, or bidirectional. This matters for future LoRa/BLE targets.\n2. The `PluginCallback` pattern -- where the plugin can notify the framework of state changes and access per-contact properties -- is worth considering. Currently reme's targets don't have a structured way to push state changes back to the coordinator (health tracking is pull-based via periodic checks).\n\n### 6. Per-Transport Key Derivation\n\n**How Briar does it (from BTP spec, `/home/leon0399/.cache/checkouts/code.briarproject.org/briar/briar-spec/protocols/BTP.md`):**\n\nThis is the most consequential difference. Briar derives **separate encryption keys for every transport**. From BTP spec section 2.4, for rotation mode:\n\n```\noutgoing_tag_key := KDF(root_key, \"ALICE_TAG_KEY\", transport_id)\noutgoing_header_key := KDF(root_key, \"ALICE_HEADER_KEY\", transport_id)\nincoming_tag_key := KDF(root_key, \"BOB_TAG_KEY\", transport_id)\nincoming_header_key := KDF(root_key, \"BOB_HEADER_KEY\", transport_id)\n```\n\nWhere `transport_id` is an ASCII string like `\"org.briarproject.bramble.bluetooth\"` or `\"org.briarproject.bramble.tor\"`.\n\nThese keys are then rotated periodically (time-period = `D + L` seconds, where D=max clock skew, L=max transport latency). Forward secrecy comes from deleting old period keys.\n\n**Why Briar does this:**\n1. **Forward secrecy per transport**: Compromising keys used on one transport doesn't affect others.\n2. **Stream recognition**: The tag-based recognition system needs per-transport keys to route incoming streams to the correct decryption context.\n3. **Different latency parameters**: Each transport has its own `maxLatency`, which determines key rotation period. Bluetooth keys rotate faster than removable-drive keys.\n4. **Transport-specific reordering windows**: Each transport maintains its own window of expected stream tags.\n\n**Should reme do this?**\n\nNo, not with reme's current MIK architecture. The designs serve different purposes:\n\n- **Briar** needs per-transport keys because it uses session-based encryption with forward secrecy. Each transport connection is a BTP stream with its own key state. Briar's encryption is transport-aware.\n- **reme** uses stateless sealed-box encryption (ephemeral X25519 + BLAKE3 KDF + ChaCha20Poly1305). Each message contains its own ephemeral key. Encryption is transport-agnostic by design -- the same `OuterEnvelope` can be relayed through any transport without re-encryption.\n\nreme's stateless approach is intentional for DTN tolerance. Introducing per-transport key derivation would:\n- Break the transport-agnostic envelope model (the same message could no longer be forwarded across transports).\n- Add complexity without clear benefit since reme has no forward secrecy anyway (MIK compromise exposes all messages regardless of transport).\n- Require session state, defeating the \"no session, no prekeys\" design.\n\n**However**, if reme ever adds forward secrecy (V2 encryption), the per-transport key derivation should be reconsidered. At that point, deriving transport-specific keys from a shared root would provide defense-in-depth -- compromising the BLE transport keys would not affect messages sent via Tor.\n\nFor now, the actionable takeaway is: reme should keep encryption transport-agnostic, which is the correct choice for a DTN-first system. But the BTP spec is excellent reference material for a future V2 encryption protocol that adds forward secrecy.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Actionable Recommendations\n\n1. **Tor transport**: If adding Tor hidden service support, use it as a transport to reach mailbox relays (like Briar's mailbox does), not for direct P2P connections. Briar's approach of per-peer hidden services is clever but high-overhead. Consider offering the relay's onion address as an alternative endpoint URL.\n\n2. **Bluetooth/BLE**: Briar proves that classic Bluetooth works point-to-point but not as mesh. For reme's Tier 3, LoRa/Meshtastic is a better investment than BLE mesh. If adding BLE, model it as a simplex, lossy, cheap transport.\n\n3. **LAN discovery**: reme's mDNS approach is the right choice for the use case (discovering unknown-contact peers for verification). Be aware of the privacy trade-off vs Briar's approach of sharing addresses only with existing contacts.\n\n4. **Mailbox**: reme's shared-relay model is more deployable than Briar's personal-mailbox model. The key lesson from Briar is the per-contact folder ID isolation -- reme's routing_key already provides this.\n\n5. **Plugin abstraction**: Consider adding `TargetCapabilities` flags for directionality (send-only, fetch-only, bidirectional) to the `TransportTarget` trait. This will matter for LoRa/BLE targets.\n\n6. **Per-transport keys**: Do NOT adopt for V1 encryption. Revisit when designing V2 forward-secrecy protocol.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>88162</total_tokens><tool_uses>46</tool_uses><duration_ms>212757</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/4ca7ec16-3e71-496c-91e6-56c7de96f6b4/tasks/a2ae3b65debd72f07.output",
